<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-530-400  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 530 400.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  August 3 1989 n1175 p64(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Virus case brings US crackdown. (Internet virus)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Millison, Doug.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US government demonstrates a hard line on hacking with thedecision to prosecute Robert T Morris, the Cornell Universitygraduate suspected of starting the 1988 Internet virus, under the1986 Computer Fraud and Abuse Act.andP;  The virus sped through 6,000computers at Internet-linked US military research sites.andP;  Morrisis the first charged under the act, which outlaws unauthorizedaccess to US government computers.andP;  Morris faces up to five yearsin prison and a $250,000 fine, but he contends he released thevirus only to test the security of the Unix-based Internetnetwork.andP;  Total cost of the virus is estimated at up to $90million.andP;  Some see little merit in the government's decision toprosecute someone with as much computer potential as Morris.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 (criminal provisions).andO;Topic:     Computer VirusesInternet (Computer network)Legal IssuesWide Area NetworksNational Government.andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>